erapy"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIron supplementation\u003C/strong\u003E is contraindicated in patients with a bone marrow failure syndrome, such as aplastic anaemia, because these patients often require frequent blood transfusions. Each transfusion introduces additional iron into the body, leading to iron overload and its potential complications. Therefore, iron supplementation is unnecessary and potentially harmful.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChemotherapy\u003C/strong\u003E may be used in certain cases of bone marrow failure, particularly if there is an underlying malignancy or as part of a conditioning regimen for bone marrow transplantation. It is not contraindicated but must be used judiciously.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProphylactic antibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E are often used in patients with bone marrow failure to prevent infections, especially when neutropenia is present. This is a common and necessary part of supportive care in these patients.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlatelet transfusions\u003C/strong\u003E are indicated in patients with severe thrombocytopenia to prevent bleeding complications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EErythropoietin therapy\u003C/strong\u003E is generally not effective in bone marrow failure syndromes like aplastic anaemia because the issue is not a lack of erythropoietin but rather a failure of the bone marrow to respond to it. However, it is not contraindicated and may be used in specific cases where there is a relative erythropoietin deficiency.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Bone marrow failure patients require supportive care including blood products, antimicrobials, and often chemotherapy or transplantation.","Iron supplementation is contraindicated in bone marrow failure as these patients typically receive frequent transfusions leading to iron overload.","Regular monitoring of iron stores is essential in transfusion-dependent patients to guide chelation therapy."],"references":["Frisch, B., \u0026 Bartl, R. (2012). Atlas of bone marrow pathology (Vol. 15). Springer Science \u0026 Business Media","Porwit, A., McCullough, J., \u0026 Erber, W. N. (2011). Blood and bone marrow pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Vissers LTW, van der Burg M, Lankester AC, Smiers FJW, Bartels M, Mohseny AB. Pediatric Bone Marrow Failure: A Broad Landscape in Need of Personalized Management. J Clin Med. 2023 Nov 20;12(22):7185. doi: 10.3390/jcm12227185. PMID: 38002797; PMCID: PMC10672506."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54741"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14806"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54741","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/54741"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-11T18:06:39+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-11T18:10:08+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7497"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69288"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","nam